msDesc.head: Hrabanus Maurus, Commentary on the Pauline Epistles, IX-XVIII.

summary.seg: Thanks to dedication inscriptions written across the end of one quire and the beginning of another, we know that the manuscript was donated to Reims Cathedral by its archbishop, Hincmar: these read 'Hincmarus archiepiscopus dedit sanctae mariae remensi' ('Archbishop Hincmar gave [this] to Saint Mary of Reims' - the cathedral being thus dedicated to the Virgin Mary). Hincmar served as archbishop between 845 and 882, which enables us to date the production of the manuscript to within this 37-year period. The survival of manuscripts whose production is dated or is datable is of great value to palaeographers, since it makes possible a more precise understanding of the chronology of the evolution in styles of medieval handwriting.

The interest of this manuscript to students of codicology, furthermore, is how clearly it illustrates the archetypical model of medieval book production in a monastic context. In order to make a book in the medieval period, one first had to obtain another copy from somewhere: this is known as the exemplar. The source of the exemplar for this manuscript is not known, nor is it known to have survived. However, it was most likely disbound and its quires divided into portions and shared among a team of scribes. These scribes were then provided with blank quires of parchment and tasked with making a copy, each working concurrently with the others and thereby speeding up the pace of production. The evidence for this may be found in a series of inscriptions at the beginning and ends of quires, presumably made by the head of the cathedral scriptorium who was co-ordinating the work, and which name the monks responsible for the copying each of these sections: first Iotsmar, then Salmon, Hrannigil, Bernard, Hrotald, Haimon, Adelrad and finally Ausold. Although all of the scribes are writing in the same style of handwriting - Caroline minuscule - their hands all differ slightly from one another, as may be seen most clearly at the transition from one scribe's stint to the next. Once their work was completed, the quires were gathered together and bound.

Thomson (supplement, 2022) has suggested that the partial erasure of 'dedit Sanctae Mariae Remensi' on f. 1r indicates that 'at least a leaf [is] missing from before Quire 1'. However, the preceding part of that inscription, 'Hincmar archiepiscopus', where it occurs elsewhere in the manuscript does so on the verso of the last leaf of the preceding quire - so it is unlikely that whatever leaf originally bore the first half of the inscription was ever structurally part of the first quire of this manuscript. The evidence in the rest of the manuscript points to the quires having been made up as a batch, and the dedication added in a similar manner, before any copying took place: this is illustrated by the loss of the second half of the inscription where the first leaf of Quire 2 has been cancelled but the text continues uninterrupted (see ff. 8v-9r). Given that this volume contains only Books IX-XVIII of Hrabanus Maurus's Commentary, one might more reasonably deduce that the preceding part of the inscription was found on the closing leaf of the preceding quire, presumably the last in an accompanying volume that bore Hrabanus's Commentary on Books I-VIII and which has been lost or remains unidentified. The partial erasure of the inscription on f. 1r might be explained by the change in ownership in the manuscript: the removal of 'dedit' and 'Remensi' reduced the inscription from the dedication of this manuscript to a more general declaration of piety by invoking the name of the Virgin Mary. The first of the two stubs that remain after Quire 1 is most likely attached to the remains of the pastedown (now f. i recto); the second is the aforementioned cancelled leaf in Quire 2.

We know that the manuscript was later in the possession of Ely Cathedral from inscriptions at the front and back of the manuscript, as well as a pressmark on f. 1r that resembles a large letter I. Simon Keynes and Michael Lapidge speculated that this manuscript might have been one of several brought from Reims to England by Grimbald of Saint-Bertin (c. 820s-901), however, as Pam Robinson notes, there is no evidence for this in the manuscript.

Dr James Freeman
Medieval Manuscripts Specialist
Cambridge University Library

foliation.note: Written in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the recto side of each leaf.

collation.p:
The manuscript comprises 33 quires, copied by a team of scribes, whose stints were divided as follows (see the description of handwriting for further details):
Iotsmar: Quires 1-6
Salmon: Quires 7-9
Hrannigil: Quires 10-12
Bernard: Quires 13-15
Hrotald: Quires 16-19
Haimon: Quires 20-22
Adelrad: Quires 23-26
Ausold: Quires 27-29
'Common portion': Quires 30-33

The quires are mostly of eight leaves.
Quire 18 (ff. 1-8)
Quire 210-1 (ff. 9-17: 1st leaf, before f. 9, cancelled)
Quires 3-58 (ff. 18-41)
Quire 66 (ff. 42-47)
Quires 7-148 (ff. 48-111)
Quire 1510 (ff. 112-121)
Quires 16-258 (ff. 122-201)
Quire 264-1 (ff. 202-204: 4th leaf, after f. 204, cancelled)
Quires 27-328 (ff. 205-252)
Quire 338-4 (ff. 253-256: 5th-8th leaves, after f. 246, excised, probably blank)

signatures.p: Quire numbers in the lower margin of the verso of the last leaf of each quire.

layout.seg: Single columns of 35 lines, frame and line ruling in hardpoint, written above top line.

handNote.p:
Copied by at least eight scribes, each writing Caroline minuscule of the Reims school, probably early in Hincmar's period (see 'History' for further details). The beginning and end of each scribal stint, and the scribe responsible, is noted on the opening and closing leaves, which are always at the beginning and end of quires (see 'Collation' for further details).
1r: Hic incoat portio Iotsmari
47v: Et hic finit
48r: Hic incipit portio Salmoni
71v: Et hic finit
72r: Hic incipit portio Hrannigili
95v: Et hic finit
96r: Hic Incipit portio Bernardi
121v: Et hic finit
122r: Incipit portio Hrotaldi
153v: Finit portio Hrotaldi
154r: Incipit portio Haimoni
177v: Et hic finit
178r: Incipit portio Adelradi
205r: Incipit portio Ausoldi
229r: Incipit portio communis
On ff. 72r-100r, 154r-160r and 178r-180r, scriptural passages are written in rustic capitals.

note.p: Running headers inserted by late medieval hands.

binding.p: Evidence of a chain-staple on a former binding, in the form of two adjacent holes and rust marks in the lower part of the fore-edge margin of the closing leaves of the manuscript (ff. 252-256).

origin.p: One of twenty-two manuscripts made at Reims and given to the Cathedral by Archbishop Hincmar (c. 806-882; reg. 845-882).

provenance.p: 18v-19r, and passim: 'Hincmarus archiepiscopus dedit sanctae mariae remensi': donation inscription written across the verso of the final leaf of each quire and the recto of the first leaf of the following, recording the gift of the manuscript to Reims CathedralNotre-Dame de Reims (Cathedral) by Archbishop HincmarHincmar, Archbishop of Reims, approximately 806-882.

Perhaps in England by the 13th century. Inscription relating to the contents of the manuscript by an English hand: 'Rabanus super duas epistolas ad corinthios et epistolam ad galathas et epistolam ad ephesios' (f. i verso ).
At Ely CathedralEly Cathedral by the later medieval period. Ownership inscription on ff. i verso, 256v: 'Iste liber pertinet ecclesie Eliensi' (15th century). Ely pressmark on f. 1r).
In the lower right-hand margin of f. 2r, an unidentified ?pressmark: '97'.

availability.p: Researchers should note that Pembroke College's western European medieval manuscripts are housed at Cambridge University Library (CUL). Scholars who wish to consult Pembroke College manuscripts should contact the Manuscripts Reading Room at CUL to arrange their visit; all CUL admissions procedures will apply. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library. For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
